[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Ruy López, Morphy Defense (3... a6)"]
[Black "Ruy López, Morphy Defense with 5... b5 (2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Ruy López } 3... a6 { Morphy Defense } 4. Ba4 Nf6
5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 d6 7. Ng5
{ This move has the highest winrate for White in practice, but it is only the 6th most played move in the position. The Knight on  g5  defends the pawn on  e4  and threatens a Knightfork on  f7  . }
7... d5 { Black's only decent move. } 8. exd5 Nxd5
{ This is the point in the game where many Black players fail to find a good move.   Capturing White's center pawn is a huge blunder. Best would have been to play  8...Nd4  , with an equal game @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nxf7 { A Knight sacrifice on  f7  , forking Queen and Rook. } 9... Kxf7 10.
Qf3+ { Forking the King and the pinned Knight in the center. } 10... Ke6
{ Defending the Knight with the King. } 11. Nc3
{ Increasing the pressure on  d5  . } 11... Ne7 { Defending  d5  . } 12. d4
{ Breaking open the center usually is a good idea when your opponents' King is in the middle of the board! Black will have a hard time to defend this position @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@, despite being up in material. }
