[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Ruy López, Morphy Defense (3... a6)"]
[Black "Ruy López, Morphy Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Ruy López } 3... a6 { Morphy Defense } 4. Bc4 Nd4
{ A dubious move: Leaving the pawn on  e5  undefended, setting up a trap. This position is very similar to a position in the Italian Game, Schilling-Kostic Gambit. }
5. Nxe5
{ Grabbing the poisoned pawn...   5.Nxd4  exd4  6.O-O  would have been better for White @@StartBracket@@+1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Qg5 { Activating the Queen, forking the Knight and the pawn on  g2  . } 6.
Nxf7
{ A game-ending blunder.   After  6.Bxf7+  , White still is in the game in view of  6...Kd8  7.O-O  Qxe5  . He has a piece less, but Black has lost his castling rights @@StartBracket@@-0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Qxg2
{ Threatening to capture the Rook in the corner @@StartBracket@@checkmate@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Rf1 Qxe4+ 8. Be2
{ White refuses to sacrifice his Queen with  8.Qe2  Nxe2  , but at an even higher cost: checkmate! }
8... Nf3#
{ Smothered mate! The Bishop is pinned to the King, so the Knight can't be captured. }
