1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Ruy López } 3... Nf6 { Berlin Defense } 4. Bxc6
{ Trading a pair of minor pieces, removing the defender of  e5  . } 4... dxc6
5. Nc3 { Defending  e4  . } 5... Bc5 { Eyeing on  f2  . } 6. Nxe5
{ A dubious move. } 6... Bxf2+
{ A counter-sacrifice!   Be careful. In a lot of similar variations,  6...Qd4  is the best move. But not in this position. Because White didn't play  d3  yet, that square is available for the Knight:  7.Nd3  , saving the Knight while protecting  f7  . }
7. Kxf2 Qd4+ { Forking King and Knight on  e5  . } 8. Kf1 Qxe5
{ Material is equal, but White lost his right to castle @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. Black has about 60% winrate in this position. }
