1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Ruy López } 3... Nf6 { Berlin Defense } 4. d3
{ Protecting  e4  . } 4... Bc5 { Eyeing on  f2  . } 5. Bxc6
{ Capturing the defender of  e5  . } 5... dxc6 6. Nxe5
{ Grabbing the pawn on  e5  . But this pawn is poisoned... } 6... Qd4
{ We have seen this idea in another variation of the Ruy López: Threatening checkmate while attacking the Knight on  e5  . Nd3 to protect  f2  is impossible because there is a pawn on  d3  . }
7. Be3 { Attacking the Queen. } 7... Qxe5
{ This move is better than  7...Qxb2  in view of  8.Nc4  Qxa1  9.Bxc5  @@StartBracket@@-3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8. d4
{ Forking Queen and Bishop. White wants to regain some material, but in fact this move only makes things even worse. }
8... Qxe4 { Grabbing a center pawn, attacking  g2  . } 9. dxc5 Qxg2
{ Attacking the Rook on  h1  . } 10. Rf1 Bh3 11. Qe2 O-O-O
{ Black has a dominant position and is completely winning @@StartBracket@@-7.0@@EndBracket@@. }
