1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Ruy López } 3... Qf6
{ Defending  e5  . Don't bring your Queen out that early in the game! } 4. Nc3
{ Normal development. } 4... Nd4 { Attacking the Bishop on  b5  , a blunder. }
5. Nxd4 { Trading Knights. } 5... exd4 6. Nd5
{ Chasing the Queen while attacking  c7  . } 6... Qd6
{ Bringing the Queen into safety while defending  c7  . } 7. d3
{ The only winning move for White in this position: Defending  e4  while making sure the Bishop on  c1  can enter the game next move. }
7... c6
{ Forking two of White's minor pieces. It looks like Black is going to win a piece... Is he? }
8. Bf4 { Trapping the Queen! } 8... Qg6
{ The most aggressive move for Black, attacking  g2  . } 9. Nc7+
{ Forking King and Rook. } 9... Kd8 10. Nxa8 Qxg2 { Counter-attacking. } 11.
Qh5 { A brilliant move, sacrificing both Rooks! We will soon see why. } 11...
Qxh1+ { Grabbing material. } 12. Ke2
{ Stepping aside with the King, attacking the Queen on  h1  .   12.Kd2  is bad because it allows Black to give check with his Bishop @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Qxa1 { Capturing White's second Rook. } 13. Qxf7
{ Threatening checkmate on  c7  with the Bishop and checkmate with on  f8  with the Queen! Black is lost  (mate-in-6)  .   A possible continuation:  13...d6  14.Qxf8+  Kd7  15.Qxd6+  Ke8  16.Nc7+  Kf7  17.Bc4+  Be6  18.Qxe6+  Kf8  19.Qf7#  . }
