{ The Knight on  c6  can't capture the Queen since it is pinned to the King by the Bishop. }
5... Bd7 { Unpinning the Knight on  c6  , now Nxd4 is a threat. } 6. Bxc6
{ Exchanging a pair of minor pieces. } 6... Bxc6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Bg5
{ Piinning the Knight to the Queen. } 8... Be7
{ Developing the dark-squared Bishop while unpinning the Knight. } 9. O-O-O Qd7
{ Keeping both the options of O-O and O-O-O open. Black should have castled kingside instead. }
10. e5 { Moving forward with the e-pawn, attacking the Knight. } 10... dxe5
{ Trading a pair of pawns. } 11. Qxe5
{ Attacking the Queen with the Rook on the open d-file. } 11... Qg4
{ Black's most tricky reply, attacking  g2  but leaving  c7  unprotected. } 12.
Bxf6
{ Things could get very complicated after top-engine moves like  12.h3  or  12.h4  . I prefer to keep it simple. }
12... gxf6 13. Qxc7 Qxg2
{ Losing the initiative by capturing a poisoned pawn. This move loses instantly. }
14. Rde1 { Threatening checkmate-in-1 on  e7  . } 14... O-O 15. Rhg1
{ Black will lose the Queen next move. Game over @@StartBracket@@+8.5@@EndBracket@@! }
