{ Expanding in the center, challenging the pawn on  e5  while opening up the diagonal for the Bishop on  c1  . }
3... Bg4 { Pinning the Knight to the Queen, not the most accurate move. } 4.
dxe5 { Exchanging pawns. } 4... Bxf3
{ A zwischenzug. But trading pieces isn't the most accurate idea. } 5. Qxf3
{ Capturing the Bishop, activating the Queen. } 5... dxe5
{ Equalizing material. } 6. Bc4
{ Threatening checkmate on  f7  .   6.Qb3  is also a good move. } 6... Nf6
{ Avoiding checkmate, but overlooking White's next tactical shot. } 7. Qb3
{ Attacking  b7  while threatening to capture  f7  . } 7... Qe7
{ Black's best move: Defending  f7  with the Queen, while lining up on the  a3  -  f8  diagonal with Queen and Bishop. }
8. Qxb7
{ Threatening to capture the Rook.   In the famous Opera Game from Paul Morphy against Duke Karl of Brunswick and Count Isouard in 1858, Morphy continued with  8.Nc3  . The game ended after a beautiful checkmate pattern:  8...c6  9.Bg5  b5  10.Nxb5  cxb5  11.Bxb5+  Nbd7  12.O-O-O  Rd8  13.Rxd7  Rxd7  14.Rd1  Qe6  15.Bxd7+  Nxd7  16.Qb8+  Nxb8  17.Rd8#  . }
8... Qb4+
{ Check, forking King and Queen. This is the reason why Black should play Qe7 instead of Qd7 on move 7. }
9. Qxb4 { Trading Queens. } 9... Bxb4+
{ Check, while threatening to capture the pawn on  e4  . How to parry both threats? }
10. Bd2 { Attacking the Bishop. } 10... Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2
{ Protecting the pawn on  e4  with the Knight. White is a pawn up @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
