4. d4 { Expanding in the center, challenging the pawn on  e5  . } 4... Bg4
{ Attacking the Knight and pinning it to the Queen. } 5. dxe5
{ Not the top move according to the engine, but it's definitely a tricky one to face. Thousands of players with the Black pieces made a mistake after this move. }
5... dxe5 { 'You take my pawn so I'll take yours' isn't always best idea. } 6.
Bxf7+
{ By capturing the pawn on  e5  , Black opened up the d-file, allowing this tactic. If Black captures the Bishop, he will lose the Queen. }
6... Ke7 { Stepping out of the check, but still defending the Queen. } 7. Qxd8+
{ Trading Queens is great in this position. } 7... Kxd8 8. Nxe5
{ White now is a second pawn ahead. In addition, the Bishop on  g4  is under attack while Ng6 threatens to fork the Rook in the corner and the Bishop on  f8  @@StartBracket@@+7.0@@EndBracket@@. The tactics in this variation also work for White in case Black played c6 instead of h6 on move 3. }
