1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 { Philidor Defense } 3. Bc4 { Keeping an eye on  f7  . }
3... h6
{ A passive move, preventing Ng5. But Ng5 was impossible anyway because the Queen sees this square. }
4. d4 { Expanding in the center, challenging the pawn on  e5  . } 4... exd4 5.
c3 { An interesting pawn sacrifice in order to develop pieces even faster. }
5... dxc3 { Accepting the pawn sacrifice. } 6. Nxc3
{ Developing the Knight while capturing Black's pawn. White already has 3 pieces developed, Black none. }
6... Nf6
{ Finally, the first developing move! But it's a bad one unfortunately... } 7.
e5 { Kicking back the Knight. } 7... dxe5
{ This blunder is the most common reply.   7...d5  would have been better. The game could continu with  8.Bb3  Nh7  9.Bxd5  . Material is equal, but White has control of the center and more active pieces. }
8. Bxf7+
{ By capturing the pawn on  e5  , Black opened up the d-file, allowing this tactic. If Black captures the Bishop, he will lose the Queen. }
8... Ke7 { Stepping out of the check, but still defending the Queen. } 9. Qb3
{ Although White could have won a pawn with  9.Qxd8  Kxd8  10.Nxe5  , Stockfish likes  9.Qb3  a lot: Protecting the Bishop with the Queen, while  e5  still is under attack. }
9... Nc6 { Defending  e5  . } 10. Nh4
{ Threatening a Knight fork on  g6  , forking King and Rook, while pushing the King onto the open d-file @@StartBracket@@+6.5@@EndBracket@@. }
