[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 { Petrov Defense } 3. Nxe5 { Classical Variation } 3... Qe7
{ Attacking the Knight in the center with an early Queen move. } 4. d4
{ Defending the Knight. } 4... Nxe4 { Equalizing material, a poor move. } 5.
Bd3
{ The only move for White to get an advantage: Developing a piece while attacking the Knight and getting ready to castle. }
5... d6 { Chasing the Knight. } 6. Bxe4
{ Exchanging Knights.   6.Nf3?  fails to  6...Nc3+  with a discovered check. The Queen on  d1  will be lost @@StartBracket@@-7.5@@EndBracket@@. }
6... dxe5 7. O-O
{ An important move! If you don't castle here, Black will probably open up the e-file by capturing the pawn on  d4  . }
7... exd4
{ After you castled, taking the pawn on  d4  is bad for Black: He opened up the e-file while his own King is far from castling and his King and Queen are lined up on the e-file. }
8. Re1
{ Making use of the open e-file. White now threatens a lot of things, e.g. Qxd4, Bxb7, Bc6+,... . White is better @@StartBracket@@+3.5@@EndBracket@@. }
