1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 { Petrov Defense } 3. Nxe5 { Classical Variation } 3... Nc6
{ Stafford Gambit, popularized by Eric Rosen on his youtube channel. This is a dubious gambit against strong players, but an excellent weapon at lower levels, especially with faster time controls. }
4. Nxc6 { Without any doubt White's best move, doubling Black's pawns. } 4...
dxc6
{ Taking back with the d-pawn in order to open up the diagonal for the light-squared Bishop on  c8  . }
5. d3
{ Supporting the pawn on  e4  , a decent move.   Other moves are good too, e.g.  5.Nc3  ,  5.Qe2  or  5.Qf3  . }
5... Bc5
{ Black's most active move. White has to watch out for Ng4 and even Nxe4. } 6.
Be2 { Again a good move, parrying both Black's threats. } 6... h5
{ By far the most played move in this position, ready to play Ng4 soon. } 7. c3
{ Again White's best move without any doubt. White will play d4 next move, putting the dangerous Bishop offside. }
7... Ng4
{ A tricky move, attacking  f7  with two minor pieces. White should stick to his plan and put the Bishop offside. }
8. d4 { Attacking the Bishop. } 8... Qh4
{ Chances are that Black will agressively continue his attack, threatening Qxf7#. }
9. g3 { Bringing the Queen into the game.   9.O-O?  fails to  9...Qxh2#  . }
9... Qf6 { Renewing the threat of an attack on  f7  . } 10. Bf3
{ The best move, although  10.f3  and  10.O-O  are playable aswell. White successfully countered Black's attacks.  a4  and  h3  are good follow-ups for White @@StartBracket@@+4.0@@EndBracket@@. }
