{ Nimzowitsch Attack, Developing a piece while attacking the Knight on  e4  . }
5... Bf5
{ Defending the Knight with the Bishop. This blunder is famous because it was played by 18-year old Viswanathan Anand  (2555 FIDE)  , in the game Zapata vs. Anand @@StartBracket@@Biel, 1988@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Qe2
{ Attacking the Knight with the Queen while pinning it to the King. White threatens d3 next move. }
6... Qe7 { Unpinning the Knight. } 7. Nd5
{ A killer move from White! Black's Queen is overloaded: She is attacked but should defend  c7  while staying on the e-file to unpin the Knight.   7...Qe6  would run into  8.Nxc7+  , a family fork. }
7... Qd7 { Defending  c7  . There is no good move... } 8. d3
{ Attacking the pinned Knight in the center. Black can't save it @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@. }
