[White "7. Petrov Defense"]
[Black "Petrov Defense, Classical Variation, Stafford Gambit (6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 { Petrov Defense } 3. Nxe5 { Classical Variation } 3... Nc6
{ Stafford Gambit, popularized by Eric Rosen on his youtube channel. This is a dubious gambit against strong players, but an excellent weapon at lower levels, especially with faster time controls. }
4. Nxc6 { Without any doubt White's best move, doubling Black's pawns. } 4...
dxc6
{ Taking back with the d-pawn in order to open up the diagonal for the light-squared Bishop on  c8  . }
5. d3
{ Supporting the pawn on  e4  , a decent move.   Other moves are good too, e.g.  5.Nc3  ,  5.Qe2  or  5.Qf3  . }
5... Bc5
{ Black's most active move. White has to watch out for Ng4 and even Nxe4. } 6.
Be2 { Again a good move, parrying both Black's threats. } 6... h5
{ By far the most played move in this position, ready to play Ng4 soon. } 7.
O-O { A poor move, giving away the advantage. } 7... Ng4
{ Black's only move to keep the attack going, putting pressure at the pawns on  f2  and  h2  . }
8. h3
{ The second most played move.   It would have been better to continue the game with  8.Bxg4  hxg4  9.Bf4  , protecting  h2  @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Qd6
{ Again a necessary move to keep the attack going, threatening checkmate on  h2  . }
9. hxg4
{ Most White players fail to find a good move at this point.   9.e5  is the only move that equalizes the game. All other moves are bad. After  9...Nxe5  , the pressure is off @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
9... hxg4 { Opening up the h-file for the Rook, threatening Qh2#. } 10. g3
{ Blocking the checkmate on  h2  . } 10... Qxg3#
{ Delivering checkmate anyway! The pawn on  f2  is pinned to the King. } *

