{ Checking White's King, trying to force White to give up his castling rights. }
5. g3 { Bertin Gambit } 5... fxg3 { Threatening  g2  with a discovered check. }
6. O-O { The only move to justify White's previous move. } 6... gxh2+ 7. Kh1
{ Capturing the pawn would leave White's King too vulnerable. The King is relatively safe in the corner, shielded by a black pawn. }
7... Nh6
{ Protecting  f7  and heading for  g4  .   7...d5  would have been better. A possible continuation is  8.Bxd5  Nf6  9.Nxh4  Nxd5  10.exd5  Qxh4  . Black has a slight edge according to the engine @@StartBracket@@-1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8. d4
{ Taking full control over the center, while attacking the Knight on  h6  with the Bishop. }
8... Ng4
{ Again,  8...d5  would have been the best move. White's lead in development is huge. }
9. Bxf7+ { Sacrificing the Bishop! } 9... Kxf7
{ If  9...Kf8  ,  10.Bh5  would be crushing. Black's pieces AND Black's King are in great danger! }
10. Nxh4+ { Winning back a piece with a discovered check! } 10... Nf6
{ Trying to save the Knight... } 11. e5
{ Attacking the pinned Knight with a pawn. Black will lose another piece, and eventually the game @@StartBracket@@+9.0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

