[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Miscellaneous"]
[Black "Damiano Defense, Damiano Gambit (3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f6
{ Damiano Defense. Protecting the pawn on  e5  in this way is a blunder. } 3.
Nxe5
{ Capturing  e5  anyway. Because the f-pawn moved, the pawns on Black's kingside are seriously weakened. }
3... fxe5
{ A bad move. But if this is a poor move, why play  f6  and weaken your kingside pawns in the first place? }
4. Qh5+ { Check, forking King and pawn. } 4... Ke7
{ 4...g6  would fail to  5.Qxe5+  , forking King and Rook. We saw this motiv multiple times in other chapters. }
5. Qxe5+
{ Capturing a center pawn with check. The King has only one square to go to. }
5... Kf7 6. Bc4+ { Developing a piece with tempo: Check! } 6... Kg6 7. Qf5+
{ This move now is possible because Black's d-pawn is blocking the  c8  -  h3  diagonal for Black's Bishop on  c8  . }
7... Kh6 8. h4
{ Controlling  g5  with the h-pawn.   This move is slightly better than moves like  8.d4  or  8.d3  . }
8... g6
{ A desperate try, often played in this position. Black hopes to flee to  g7  with his King, but it is already too late... }
9. d4+ { Check with the Bishop. } 9... Kg7 10. Qf7#
{ Checkmate in only 10 moves. Never play 2... f6 as black! } *

