1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f6
{ Damiano Defense. Protecting the pawn on  e5  in this way is a blunder. } 3.
Nxe5
{ Capturing  e5  anyway. Because the f-pawn moved, the pawns on Black's kingside are seriously weakened. }
3... fxe5
{ A bad move. But if this is a poor move, why play  f6  and weaken your kingside pawns in the first place? }
4. Qh5+ { Check, forking King and pawn. } 4... Ke7
{ 4...g6  would fail to  5.Qxe5+  , forking King and Rook. We saw this motiv multiple times in other chapters. }
5. Qxe5+
{ Capturing a center pawn with check. The King has only one square to go to. }
5... Kf7 6. Bc4+ { Developing a piece with tempo: Check! } 6... d5
{ The only move to stay in the game, as we will see in other variations. This move is important for Black in order to open up the diagonal for the Bishop, to defend  f5  later in the game. }
7. Bxd5+ Kg6 { 7...Be6  8.Qxe6#  . } 8. h4
{ Threatening h5 next move, with a deadly attack. } 8... h6
{ Creating an escape square for the King on  h7  . Keep in mind that if there was no Bishop on  c8  , Qf5 would have been checkmate! }
9. Bxb7 { A brilliant move!   9...Bxb7  would result in  10.Qf5#  . } 9... Bd6
{ Attacking the Queen while developing a piece. } 10. Qa5
{ Keep in mind that the Queen has to keep an eye on  f5  to deliver checkmate in case Black decides to capture the Bishop on  b7  . White will capture the Rook next move @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@. White got a Rook and 4 pawns in return for the sacrificed Knight on move 2. }
