{ Wayward Queen Attack, Bringing the Queen out early to attack the pawn on  e5  . A poor move according to club players, but a  playable move in case you and your opponent both are beginners or casual players. }
2... Nc6 { Developing a piece while defending the pawn on  e5  . } 3. Bc4
{ Threatening checkmate on  f7  already! } 3... g6 { Preventing checkmate. } 4.
Qf3 { Threatening checkmate again. } 4... Nf6
{ Preventing checkmate while developing a piece. } 5. Nh3
{ A blunder. White is only focused on agressive moves, but you have to watch out for a possible counter attack from your opponent. }
5... Nd4 { Attacking White's Queen while threatening a nasty fork on  c2  . }
6. Qd3
{ 6.Qd1  would have been better. Best continuation for Black is  6...d5  , with the idea of  7.exd5  Bg4  @@StartBracket@@-4.5@@EndBracket@@. }
6... d5
{ Attacking White's Bishop and center pawn, while opening the diagonal for his Bishop. }
7. exd5 Bf5
{ Developing a piece while attacking the Queen and the pawn on  c2  behind it @@StartBracket@@-7.0@@EndBracket@@. }
