[White "9. Miscellaneous"]
[Black "Latvian Gambit Accepted, Main Line (2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5 { Latvian Gambit } 3. Nxe5 { Latvian Gambit Accepted } 3...
Qf6 { Attacking the Knight in the center. } 4. d4
{ Main Line, Defending the Knight. } 4... d6
{ Attacking the Knight once again. } 5. Nf3
{ A poor move.   5.Nc4  is better, e.g. followed by  5...fxe4  6.Nc3  Qg6  . }
5... fxe4 6. Bg5
{ Attacking the Queen. This is a mistake, because the defender of this Bishop is already under attack. }
6... Qg6 { Staying near the Bishop. } 7. Qe2
{ Pinning the pawn. White doesn't want to move the Knight, since it's job is to defend the Bishop on  g5  . }
7... Be7
{ Unpinning the pawn while attacking White's Bishop with a second piece. White will lose either the Knight or the Bishop next move. }
8. Bxe7
{ By far the most played move in the position. Keep in mind the pawn on  e4  isn't pinned to the King anymore! }
8... exf3
{ Equalizing material while attacking both the Queen and Bishop at the same time. White can save the Queen, but will lose the Bishop next move @@StartBracket@@-5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
