1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 { Ponziani Opening } 3... d5
{ Expanding in the center. } 4. Bd3
{ Defending the pawn on  e4  with the Bishop. It is almost never a good idea to block your own center pawns with a piece. Take a look at White's queenside: All those pieces will be locked in for a while!   4.d4  ,  4.d3  or even  4.Qa4  would have been a better move. }
4... Nf6 { The strongest move, attacking  e4  with an extra piece. } 5. exd5
{ This suboptimal move is the most played move in this position.   A better option for White was:  5.Qe2  , e.g. followed by  5...dxe4  6.Bxe4  Nxe4  7.Qxe4  Bd6  , going for  f5  in the next couple moves @@StartBracket@@-1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Qxd5
{ Capturing with the Queen since it can't be chased away by a Knight. In addition, the Queen attacks the Bishop on  d3  . }
6. Bc2 { Retreating the Bishop. } 6... e4
{ Attacking the Knight, taking even more space!   The game could continue with  7.Qe2  Be6  , unpinning the e-pawn,  8.Nd4  Nxd4  9.cxd4  O-O-O  @@StartBracket@@-4.0@@EndBracket@@. }
